name: Tails
description: Tails is a portable operating system that protects against surveillance and censorship.
sites_https_justification: The website (https://tails.boum.org) also used for downloads and repository (https://gitlab.tails.boum.org) both use HTTPS.
description_good_justification: The home page of Tails (https://tails.boum.org/) describes in less than 1000 characters supported by graphics the purpose of Tails: Tails is a portable operating system that protects against surveillance and censorship.
interact_justification: There is a dedicated page for contributing on Tails website (https://tails.boum.org/contribute/).
contribution_justification: Instructions for code contributors are  available on the page https://tails.boum.org/contribute/how/code/
contribution_requirements_justification: The process for contributing code is described on the page https://tails.boum.org/contribute/merge_policy/
license_location_justification: File COPYING at the root of the project contains the license: https://gitlab.tails.boum.org/tails/tails/-/blob/stable/COPYING
floss_license_justification: Tails source code is released under license GPLv3+ (https://tails.boum.org/doc/about/license/) The GPL-3.0-or-later license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The GPL-3.0-or-later license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: Tails website contains extensive user documentation: https://tails.boum.org/doc/
documentation_interface_justification: Tails is meant to be used by humans, therefore its input and output is defined by how it is used, which is detailed in its user documentation.
repo_public_justification: Tails repository https://gitlab.tails.boum.org/tails/tails is publicly readable.
repo_track_justification: Tails repository is a GitLab instance with all facilities for version control.
repo_distributed_justification: Git
release_notes_justification: Release notes are available from the Tails website: https://tails.boum.org/news/
release_notes_vulns_justification: Release notes contain a section "Fixed problems" but these typically don't contain vulnerabilities, as Tails source code is small. Vulnerabilities in dependencies like Tor or Debian are tracked in these other projects.
report_tracker_justification: Tails uses a GitLab instance for its issues tracker at https://gitlab.tails.boum.org/tails/tails/-/issues/
report_process_justification: Tails website describes the process to report an error: https://tails.boum.org/doc/first_steps/bug_reporting/
report_responses_justification:
An initial answer to a bug report on GitLab is typically sent within 2 weeks.

User feedback sent with Tails' custom error reporting tool (WhisperBack) is used as a source of information
to identify trends, recurring problems, and important regressions. They are only answered if the Tails Help Desk needs further information. We're working on sending an automated acknowledgment to such messages: https://gitlab.tails.boum.org/tails/tails/-/issues/17935
enhancement_responses_justification: An initial answer to an enhancement request on GitLab is typically sent within 2 weeks.
report_archive_justification: The GitLab instance used by Tails archives all issues and allows searching through issues: https://gitlab.tails.boum.org/tails/tails/-/issues/
vulnerability_report_process_justificati:
Vulnerabilities should be reported to a private, encrypted mailing list:
https://tails.boum.org/about/contact/#tails
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: The email contact for reporting vulnerabilities is private and OpenPGP-enabled: https://tails.boum.org/about/contact/#tails
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: no vulnerabilities reported in the last 6 months
build_justification: The process for building an USB and ISO image of Tails is fully automated and documented on https://tails.boum.org/contribute/build/
build_common_tools_justification: Tails uses Rake (http://ruby.github.io/rake) and Vagrant (https://www.vagrantup.com/) for building.
build_floss_tools_justification: The build instructions describe all dependencies for building, which are all FLOSS.
test_justification: The testsuite is maintained in sub-directory "features" of the Tails repository, and can be run automatically with the script "run_test_suite" as documented in https://tails.boum.org/contribute/release_process/test/automated_tests/
test_invocation_justification: The test suite for Tails is using standard tools for simulating the Tor network and user actions.
test_most_justification: Test suite coverage is required for new major functionality and significant behavior changes.
tests_documented_added_justification: Instructions for developers mention both the possibility to work on tests, and the requirement to test changes before submitting them, see https://tails.boum.org/contribute/how/code/
warnings_justification: Individual developers use linters but this is not fully integrated in our CI yet (except shellcheck).
warnings_fixed_justification: We block merge requests on shellcheck errors.
warnings_strict_justification: We are strict about shellcheck warnings.
crypto_published_justification: Tails' custom error reporting tool (WhisperBack) used OpenPGP as implemented in GnuPG for message encryption. Tails' data at rest encryption uses LUKS. Tails Upgrader uses GnuPG.
crypto_call_justification:
WhisperBack uses the gnupg Python module which wraps calls to GnuPG.
GnuPG, LUKS, and VeraCrypt are specifically designed to implement cryptographic functions.
crypto_floss_justification: GnuPG, LUKS, and VeraCrypt are FLOSS.
crypto_keylength_justification:
WhisperBack is using RSA keys of length 4096 bits, while the NIST minimum through year 2030 for RSA is 2048 bits according to https://www.keylength.com/en/4/. 

LUKS and VeraCrypt use AES with keys of 256 bits, while the NIST minimum through year 2030 for AES is 128 bits according to https://www.keylength.com/en/4/.
crypto_working_justification:
GnuPG, LUKS, and VeraCrypt are not using broken cryptographic algorithms.

Cryptographic libraries installed from Debian, such as OpenSSL, don't use any either.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: This is part of Tails' mission statement.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The project does not produce software written in a memory-unsafe language that handles untrusted input.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: PGP, LUKS, and VeraCrypt are not using cryptographic algorithms or modes with known serious weaknesses.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Tails uses Jenkins for CI, as documented in https://tails.boum.org/contribute/working_together/roles/sysadmins/automated_tests_in_Jenkins/
discussion_justification: Tails uses a GitLab instance for its issues tracker at https://gitlab.tails.boum.org/tails/tails/-/issues/
english_justification:
Documentation is available in English: https://tails.boum.org/doc/
The project uses English for its issue tracker: https://gitlab.tails.boum.org/tails/tails/-/issues/
Bug reporting: https://tails.boum.org/doc/first_steps/bug_reporting/
